of trying to find the dress?

911
01:05:24,505 --> 01:05:27,174
- I love that dress.
- Yeah, it's good.

912
01:05:27,341 --> 01:05:31,345
It makes sense too, because
it's not an expensive dress, you know.

913
01:05:31,512 --> 01:05:32,596
Great choice.

914
01:05:32,846 --> 01:05:36,100
M.J., would you do me a favor?
I forgot my drink inside.

915
01:05:39,686 --> 01:05:42,147
I also like that line where he says:

916
01:05:42,314 --> 01:05:46,527
"Why didn't you wear the black dress?
My father loves black."

917
01:05:46,735 --> 01:05:48,445
It is a funny line.

918
01:05:49,530 --> 01:05:54,701
- Have you seen my father around?
- Well, I'm not sure if he's coming.

919
01:05:54,868 --> 01:06:00,040
This was, without question, the most
complicated thing we did in the movie.

920
01:06:00,207 --> 01:06:02,543
Even more complicated than the end.

921
01:06:02,751 --> 01:06:04,336
We would have these meetings.

922
01:06:04,503 --> 01:06:08,048
We would have these weekly
or bi-weekly, or sometimes daily...

923
01:06:08,215 --> 01:06:10,217
...what we called
"Times Square meetings."

924
01:06:10,384 --> 01:06:12,886
Starting from when we made
the decision...

925
01:06:13,053 --> 01:06:15,305
...to set this scene in Times Square.

926
01:06:15,514 --> 01:06:19,810
The logistics of how to do it
and how to get the shots.

927
01:06:20,018 --> 01:06:24,982
The building where you guys are on
the balcony is a building Neil made up.

928
01:06:25,149 --> 01:06:29,736
It doesn't really exist in Times Square,
but we had to fit it in geographically.

929
01:06:29,903 --> 01:06:34,908
And there were plates that were shot
for this stuff up in the sky.

930
01:06:35,075 --> 01:06:39,037
And then there was a gigantic set
built in Downey.

931
01:06:39,204 --> 01:06:45,002
So even though
it's a five-minute sequence...

932
01:06:45,210 --> 01:06:49,673
...in terms of the resources
and the shooting time...

933
01:06:49,882 --> 01:06:55,804
...we probably shot, between the set
and the location, three weeks maybe.

934
01:06:56,013 --> 01:06:58,432
- Close to a month.
- It was a big deal.

935
01:07:00,434 --> 01:07:02,728
There was Stan Lee.
There's Stan Lee.

936
01:07:03,437 --> 01:07:08,400
- Laura's daughter is coming in soon.
- My daughter. The stuntman who fell...

937
01:07:08,609 --> 01:07:11,737
...was a guy who played Spider-Man
on the TV show.

938
01:07:12,529 --> 01:07:14,948
Remember that?
Here we go, Kirsten.

939
01:07:15,115 --> 01:07:18,452
Here starts the screaming match.
Hold your ears.

940
01:07:18,619 --> 01:07:20,037
"Oh, God!"

941
01:07:20,204 --> 01:07:23,790
I kept telling Sam...
I love that shot.

942
01:07:24,833 --> 01:07:28,462
Girls in movies who scream
really annoy me.

943
01:07:28,629 --> 01:07:31,924
At the end, I got a little annoyed
by my screaming.

944
01:07:32,132 --> 01:07:34,259
At the end of the movie.

945
01:07:38,305 --> 01:07:41,808
I love that.
That's one of my favorite things.

946
01:07:42,643 --> 01:07:47,981
The pumpkin bomb was kind of fun
because the Goblin was full of...

947
01:07:48,148 --> 01:07:50,567
- There's my daughter.
- Yeah. Hi, Julie.

948
01:07:52,653 --> 01:07:54,947
The Goblin has this bag of tricks...

949
01:07:55,155 --> 01:07:57,491
...and when we were sitting
and thinking about it:

950
01:07:57,658 --> 01:08:02,412
"What would a pumpkin bomb look like?
Who would think of such a thing?"

951
01:08:03,580 --> 01:08:07,501
This kid's stupid. I know he's
in shock, but move, already!

952
01:08:07,668 --> 01:08:10,879
Wouldn't your mother go in
and move you?

953
01:08:11,088 --> 01:08:14,466
- She couldn't get to him.
- Oh, yeah, whatever.

954
01:08:15,008 --> 01:08:17,010
- Hold it!
- I surrender.

955
01:08:17,177 --> 01:08:20,180
Willem demanded to do
all his own fighting.

956
01:08:20,931 --> 01:08:25,102
He felt that the character
had to be consistent...

957
01:08:25,310 --> 01:08:29,481
...and that it would show if he
let stuntmen do his work.

958
01:08:29,648 --> 01:08:31,483
It wouldn't sell.

959
01:08:32,526 --> 01:08:36,863
Not that the quality would be poor,
but it wouldn't be the same character...

960
01:08:37,030 --> 01:08:39,908
...that he'd created and seen through
from beginning to end.

961
01:08:41,118 --> 01:08:43,912
In this strafing run,
this is him on the glider right there.

962
01:08:44,121 --> 01:08:47,332
That's right, that behind shot.
Shot by Max Kleven.

963
01:08:47,499 --> 01:08:52,212
It's really a good... Well-designed
glider gag that Max came up with...

964
01:08:52,796 --> 01:08:56,717
...hanging off of the camera car,
on a Ubangi on wires.

965
01:08:56,925 --> 01:08:58,885
It worked beautifully.

966
01:09:03,849 --> 01:09:09,021
The storyboard artists, mostly Doug
Lefter, did a great job designing all this.

967
01:09:09,229 --> 01:09:13,066
He had help from Neil Spisak
and the production department...

968
01:09:13,317 --> 01:09:15,652
...with balloons and the set.

969
01:09:15,861 --> 01:09:17,904
Also,
Jeff Lynch and Dave Stephan...

970
01:09:18,071 --> 01:09:20,699
...contributed a tremendous amount
to this.

971
01:09:21,908 --> 01:09:25,412
But my hat's off to Doug.
He's such a great visualist.

972
01:09:28,874 --> 01:09:30,709
This sequence is complicated.

973
01:09:30,917 --> 01:09:36,256
Andrew Jimenez really added a lot
with his skills...

974
01:09:36,465 --> 01:09:38,342
...working this whole sequence out.

975
01:09:38,508 --> 01:09:42,095
Karen Goulekas contributed quite a bit
on the picture.

976
01:09:42,346 --> 01:09:47,517
John Dykstra and the animation team
made each and every shot come to life.

977
01:09:47,684 --> 01:09:51,772
But it couldn't have been put together
unless we had Bob Murawski...

978
01:09:51,938 --> 01:09:56,777
...who worked the pieces as the editor
and made them all come together.

979
01:09:57,235 --> 01:10:00,155
That was a great swinging shot
by our stuntman.

980
01:10:00,322 --> 01:10:05,118
Jeff Habberstad put together this shot
over the blue sky over the ocean...

981
01:10:05,285 --> 01:10:08,288
...because there're no
green screens that big.

982
01:10:08,497 --> 01:10:12,542
They shot that out at the ocean.
It's a beautiful swing.

983
01:10:15,754 --> 01:10:21,718
Neil Spisak really came up with a
beautifully romantic location here...

984
01:10:21,927 --> 01:10:24,638
...for the moment between
Peter and Mary Jane.

985
01:10:24,805 --> 01:10:28,517
He did his homework. Many
New Yorkers don't know this exists...

986
01:10:29,101 --> 01:10:32,270
...on top of the Rockefeller Center
roof garden.

987
01:10:32,646 --> 01:10:36,775
It is such a beautiful place up there,
with the church in the background.

988
01:10:47,035 --> 01:10:49,454
Starting to swing a little better.

989
01:10:51,456 --> 01:10:57,671
I love when he swings off and yells.
It's like the high of public service.

990
01:10:57,838 --> 01:11:02,426
You've done your best to help others
and that's what he's celebrating.

991
01:11:02,592 --> 01:11:04,344
That's really why it's so effective.

992
01:11:04,511 --> 01:11:07,347
And he runs along that building.
I love that moment.

993
01:11:07,514 --> 01:11:10,851
The fellas in the animation department
came up with that.

994
01:11:11,059 --> 01:11:14,688
I think it was Anthony,
our animation director.

995
01:11:14,855 --> 01:11:17,190
And what do you mean,
incredible?

996
01:11:20,026 --> 01:11:22,362
All right. I'm sorry. Sleep tight.

997
01:11:22,571 --> 01:11:24,322
Don't let the bedbugs...

998
01:11:25,991 --> 01:11:28,660
Alvin Sargent wrote that scene.
It's one of my favorites.

999
01:11:28,869 --> 01:11:32,956
So funny, with James Franco
on the phone with M.J.

1000
01:11:33,165 --> 01:11:37,127
You just imagine, obviously,
the other side of the conversation.

1001
01:11:38,211 --> 01:11:40,964
And then, after being dumped on...

1002
01:11:41,131 --> 01:11:46,011
...he hangs up the phone and he says,
"She's just a little rattled."

1003
01:11:46,386 --> 01:11:49,055
What else would he be thinking?

1004
01:11:49,222 --> 01:11:50,724
I didn't.

1005
01:11:54,603 --> 01:11:57,022
I'm gonna get some rest.

1006
01:11:58,231 --> 01:12:00,525
I'm gonna stay up for a while.

1007
01:12:01,610 --> 01:12:03,361
What was that thing?

1008
01:12:03,904 --> 01:12:05,238
I don't know.

1009
01:12:06,698 --> 01:12:10,076
Whatever it is,
somebody has to stop it.

1010
01:12:10,744 --> 01:12:12,996
That moment was important to me...

1011
01:12:13,163 --> 01:12:19,252
...because it was Peter Parker stepping
up to the responsibility of Spider-Man.

1012
01:12:25,926 --> 01:12:27,636
Somebody there?

1013
01:12:27,886 --> 01:12:29,930
<i>Somebody.</i>

1014
01:12:31,264 --> 01:12:32,766
Who said that?

1015
01:12:33,183 --> 01:12:37,062
This sequence with Willem takes you
to depths of the insanity...

1016
01:12:37,270 --> 01:12:42,359
...that his character is starting
to plummet down into.

1017
01:12:44,528 --> 01:12:46,821
I love the device you came up with...

1018
01:12:46,988 --> 01:12:51,034
...with the mirror showing
his two different personalities...

1019
01:12:51,201 --> 01:12:53,787
...and interacting with his
two different personalities.

1020
01:12:53,954 --> 01:12:56,540
You know, that was in the script.

1021
01:12:57,040 --> 01:12:59,960
It was all made to work...

1022
01:13:00,126 --> 01:13:04,256
...just only through Willem Dafoe's
performance.

1023
01:13:04,965 --> 01:13:08,176
Did you think it was coincidence?

1024
01:13:08,426 --> 01:13:11,972
So many good things,
all happening for you.

1025
01:13:12,138 --> 01:13:15,809
All for you. Norman.

1026
01:13:18,311 --> 01:13:19,771
What do you want?

1027
01:13:20,313 --> 01:13:22,315
To say what you won't.

1028
01:13:22,649 --> 01:13:25,151
To do what you can't.

1029
01:13:25,318 --> 01:13:29,948
To remove those in your way.

1030
01:13:33,910 --> 01:13:35,829
The board members.

1031
01:13:37,163 --> 01:13:38,498
You killed them.

1032
01:13:38,707 --> 01:13:40,250
We killed them.

1033
01:13:40,584 --> 01:13:41,626
We?

1034
01:13:41,835 --> 01:13:45,088
Remember?
Your little accident...

1035
01:13:45,255 --> 01:13:47,924
It's this lesson you learn
all the time...

1036
01:13:48,091 --> 01:13:52,596
...about how much you need
to communicate, for the story...

1037
01:13:52,762 --> 01:13:57,934
...what's going on, and how much
an actor brings to the storytelling.

1038
01:13:58,101 --> 01:14:02,355
Initially written, it was a three
and a half page scene, or something.

1039
01:14:02,522 --> 01:14:07,027
And the revelation as we went along
in the process was...

1040
01:14:07,235 --> 01:14:10,864
...you could get everything you had
to get from a storytelling standpoint...

1041
01:14:11,364 --> 01:14:16,036
...as well as the emotional stuff
that was going on with the character...

1042
01:14:16,244 --> 01:14:18,455
...much more economically.

1043
01:14:19,873 --> 01:14:23,043
Spider-Man. And the Green Goblin.

1044
01:14:23,335 --> 01:14:26,546
The Green Goblin. You like that?
Made it up myself.

1045
01:14:26,755 --> 01:14:29,716
- These weirdos all got to have a name.
- Mr. Jameson, Spider...

1046
01:14:29,883 --> 01:14:31,551
- Hoffman!
- Yeah?

1047
01:14:32,802 --> 01:14:36,556
Copyright the name "Green Goblin."
I want a quarter every time it's said.

1048
01:14:36,765 --> 01:14:39,059
How about "Green Meanie"?

1049
01:14:39,225 --> 01:14:42,062
Spider-Man wasn't attacking the city.
That's slander.

1050
01:14:42,270 --> 01:14:44,564
It is not. I resent that.

1051
01:14:44,856 --> 01:14:47,567
Slander is spoken.
In print, it's libel.

1052
01:14:47,776 --> 01:14:49,402
You don't trust anybody.

1053
01:14:49,903 --> 01:14:51,655
I trust my barber.

1054
01:14:52,322 --> 01:14:53,990
What are you, his lawyer? Get out.

1055
01:14:54,199 --> 01:14:58,912
Let him sue. Get rich like a normal
person. That's what made this country...

1056
01:15:04,084 --> 01:15:08,088
I remember shooting that scene with
the cigar flying back into the window.

1057
01:15:08,254 --> 01:15:14,511
Usually it missed the table, sometimes
it landed in J.K.'s lap, burning him.

1058
01:15:14,678 --> 01:15:18,431
It's a dangerous scene, to have
that hot thing flying in from behind.

1059
01:15:18,598 --> 01:15:20,600
One of my favorites to shoot.

1060
01:15:20,767 --> 01:15:22,102
You are useless.

1061
01:15:22,268 --> 01:15:26,231
Jane Alexander did such a great job
with his hair.

1062
01:15:26,398 --> 01:15:30,026
It's so J. Jonah Jameson. He's great.

1063
01:15:30,443 --> 01:15:32,570
...let Mom and Dad
talk for a minute.

1064
01:15:32,779 --> 01:15:35,240
Sleep...

1065
01:15:49,713 --> 01:15:53,717
Wake up, little spider. Wake up.

1066
01:15:53,883 --> 01:15:58,304
No, you're not dead yet.

1067
01:15:58,471 --> 01:16:00,640
Just paralyzed...

1068
01:16:00,849 --> 01:16:02,809
...temporarily.

1069
01:16:03,810 --> 01:16:06,896
You're an amazing creature,
Spider-Man.

1070
01:16:07,105 --> 01:16:09,774
You and I are not so different.

1071
01:16:10,483 --> 01:16:13,820
I'm not like you. You're a murderer.

1072
01:16:13,987 --> 01:16:16,906
Well, to each his own.

1073
01:16:17,073 --> 01:16:19,993
I chose my path,
you chose the way of the hero.

1074
01:16:20,660 --> 01:16:25,331
And they found you amusing
for a while, the people of this city.

1075
01:16:25,498 --> 01:16:28,793
But the one thing they love
more than a hero...

1076
01:16:29,002 --> 01:16:32,589
...is to see a hero fail,
fall, die trying.

1077
01:16:32,756 --> 01:16:37,302
In spite of everything you've done for
them, eventually, they will hate you.

1078
01:16:37,510 --> 01:16:38,511
Why bother?

1079
01:16:38,762 --> 01:16:43,475
- Because it's right.
- Here's the real truth.

1080
01:16:43,892 --> 01:16:46,895
There are eight million people
in this city.

1081
01:16:47,187 --> 01:16:51,649
This whole notion of trying to see,
at least see the eyes...

1082
01:16:51,816 --> 01:16:56,529
...even though we couldn't see
any of Tobey's features...

1083
01:16:56,696 --> 01:17:00,825
The genius of what Sam did
in the end of the movie was find a way...

1084
01:17:01,034 --> 01:17:06,206
...to reveal Tobey's face
in the final scenes.

1085
01:17:06,414 --> 01:17:09,375
Because as you can see,
looking at this...

1086
01:17:09,542 --> 01:17:15,048
...you're limited in how you can act
behind those masks.

1087
01:17:15,715 --> 01:17:17,717
Or we could destroy.

1088
01:17:17,926 --> 01:17:21,888
Cause the deaths of countless
innocents in selfish battle...

1089
01:17:22,055 --> 01:17:26,976
...again and again and again until
we're both dead. Is that what you want?

1090
01:17:27,185 --> 01:17:31,898
Great animation from the fellas at SPI.
I love him leaping on that glider.

1091
01:17:32,065 --> 01:17:36,236
He seems like he's gotta balance
himself for a brief moment.

1092
01:17:36,486 --> 01:17:41,074
He gotta grab a hold of the front of
the glider to stabilize himself.

1093
01:17:41,241 --> 01:17:43,243
- Seems very real to me.
- Yeah.

1094
01:17:43,827 --> 01:17:49,165
<i>In spite of everything you've done for
them, eventually, they will hate you.</i>

1095
01:17:56,589 --> 01:18:00,260
This was also shot
on the Warner Bros. back lot.

1096
01:18:01,177 --> 01:18:02,387
How was your audition?

1097
01:18:02,554 --> 01:18:05,098
The sound man gave me
an ugly choice. He said:

1098
01:18:05,265 --> 01:18:09,853
"You can have oars in the background,
or you can have your sound."

1099
01:18:10,061 --> 01:18:11,938
Horrible thing to say.

1100
01:18:13,690 --> 01:18:18,611
They made so much noise going over
those wet city streets, those cabs.

1101
01:18:19,070 --> 01:18:22,115
Motion picture cabs are always
in terrible shape.

1102
01:18:22,282 --> 01:18:26,286
Loud engines, terribly in need
of a tune up.

1103
01:18:27,787 --> 01:18:33,543
This is my favorite scene between
the two of them. I really, really enjoy it.

1104
01:18:35,461 --> 01:18:36,880
I'd like a cheeseburger.

1105
01:18:37,046 --> 01:18:40,049
Alvin Sargent wrote this.
Did a beautiful job with it too.

1106
01:18:40,216 --> 01:18:41,968
He did a great job.

1107
01:18:42,135 --> 01:18:43,595
Come with us.

1108
01:18:43,761 --> 01:18:46,514
No, thanks. How's it going with...?

1109
01:18:48,433 --> 01:18:50,935
Never mind.
That's none of my business.

1110
01:18:51,436 --> 01:18:52,937
It's not?

1111
01:18:54,314 --> 01:18:56,024
Why so interested?

1112
01:18:56,316 --> 01:18:59,402
Avi Arad had a great idea during
this scene.

1113
01:18:59,569 --> 01:19:03,656
He said, "Maybe this is the point
where she can finally say 'Tiger."'

1114
01:19:03,948 --> 01:19:10,455
Which is what all the fans know is one
of Mary Jane's favorite taglines.

1115
01:19:10,622 --> 01:19:12,123
I don't know.

1116
01:19:12,332 --> 01:19:16,753
So Kirsten then said, "Why don't I say it
just as I leave, at the very end?"

1117
01:19:17,003 --> 01:19:22,050
So together, they satisfied that one
of one thousand fan requirements.

1118
01:19:22,300 --> 01:19:24,928
It's a great little punctuation mark.

1119
01:19:30,350 --> 01:19:32,352
Hey, check it out, man.

1120
01:19:32,518 --> 01:19:34,187
Come on, man.

1121
01:19:34,479 --> 01:19:38,107
This scene was further torturing
of Kirsten...

1122
01:19:38,316 --> 01:19:42,695
...in very, very cold weather
and freezing cold water.

1123
01:19:43,446 --> 01:19:45,198
This wasn't a fun scene.

1124
01:19:45,490 --> 01:19:47,825
Although I did like
to do my little butt-kicking.

1125
01:19:47,992 --> 01:19:49,202
You did.

1126
01:19:50,995 --> 01:19:54,374
See, the sidewalks are higher
on the back lot...

1127
01:19:54,666 --> 01:19:57,794
...so the water floods in the street.

1128
01:19:58,044 --> 01:20:01,130
You're up to water on your ankle.

1129
01:20:03,299 --> 01:20:06,678
This was tough because we were
all bundled up in front of heaters...

1130
01:20:07,095 --> 01:20:11,683
- ...and you were out there for hours.
- Freezing my booty off.

1131
01:20:13,351 --> 01:20:16,396
And trying to be romantic
at the same time.

1132
01:20:18,231 --> 01:20:22,902
When we were doing the close-up
dialogue without the looping...

1133
01:20:23,152 --> 01:20:26,489
...I was screaming at him.
I was like, "You're amazing!"

1134
01:20:26,739 --> 01:20:31,494
Because we couldn't hear each other
because the rain was so loud.

1135
01:20:34,205 --> 01:20:37,583
There was a secret door built
into the side of that wall...

1136
01:20:37,834 --> 01:20:42,422
...so that Tobey could escape into it and
the stuntman could then come down.

1137
01:20:42,714 --> 01:20:44,674
Although, this is Tobey here.

1138
01:20:45,008 --> 01:20:50,263
But the first time you saw Spider-Man
descend was the stuntman.

1139
01:20:50,847 --> 01:20:52,223
Does she know or doesn't she?

1140
01:20:52,390 --> 01:20:54,851
You have that moment
where maybe you know it's him?

1141
01:20:55,059 --> 01:20:56,561
Here? No. That's at the end.

1142
01:20:56,769 --> 01:21:00,106
But when he says,
"I was in the neighborhood."

1143
01:21:00,356 --> 01:21:03,401
No? That's what I always think
because he said to you earlier on:

1144
01:21:03,568 --> 01:21:04,902
"I was in the neighborhood."

1145
01:21:05,153 --> 01:21:09,115
No, I don't think M.J.'s that bright.
Or Kirsten.

1146
01:21:09,282 --> 01:21:13,453
No, no, I just...
I wouldn't give anything away there.

1147
01:21:13,745 --> 01:21:16,956
There was this wonderful image
in the comic book of him...

1148
01:21:17,165 --> 01:21:21,127
...with his, you know,
mask half off like that.

1149
01:21:21,294 --> 01:21:25,465
It was something that Sam had
in his head very early on...

1150
01:21:25,715 --> 01:21:29,677
...to have this upside-down kiss
which is so...

1151
01:21:29,927 --> 01:21:36,392
I know it was painful, but it really
is his signature moment of the movie.

1152
01:21:36,601 --> 01:21:41,773
Our mixers, Greg Russell and Kevin
O'Connell did a great job mixing this.

1153
01:21:41,981 --> 01:21:45,443
This scene, they handled
just beautifully, like the old movies.

1154
01:21:45,693 --> 01:21:49,989
They let the rain all drop away,
brought up Danny Elf man's score.

1155
01:21:50,239 --> 01:21:53,618
They let the audience soar
with the emotion of the thing...

1156
01:21:53,785 --> 01:21:56,829
...pushing away the reality
of the moment.

1157
01:22:15,515 --> 01:22:17,850
Let me in! My baby's in there!

1158
01:22:18,017 --> 01:22:21,604
This was a great piece
of location work in New York.

1159
01:22:21,813 --> 01:22:24,607
I was very impressed
that they let us...

1160
01:22:24,816 --> 01:22:29,112
...blaze that building
as large as we needed to.

1161
01:22:29,320 --> 01:22:32,532
We owe a great debt
to the city of New York for that.

1162
01:22:32,865 --> 01:22:35,618
John Fedynich, he was our New York
location manager.

1163
01:22:35,868 --> 01:22:41,332
He did a lot of great work securing
the permits and permission to do that.

1164
01:22:41,541 --> 01:22:46,045
When he swings into that window,
the one piece of animation I love...

1165
01:22:46,337 --> 01:22:50,675
...is when the animator lets his web
get caught in the updraft of the heat.

1166
01:22:50,883 --> 01:22:56,639
And it just floats upward in a moment,
right before the cut.

1167
01:22:56,848 --> 01:23:01,352
It really captured
the lightness of the web.

1168
01:23:07,233 --> 01:23:11,237
- It's okay. Your baby's fine.
- Oh, my baby!

1169
01:23:12,280 --> 01:23:14,699
God bless you, Spider-Man.

1170
01:23:14,907 --> 01:23:18,077
The blanket has no dirt
on it or anything.

1171
01:23:18,369 --> 01:23:20,580
Now, come on, you guys.

1172
01:23:20,788 --> 01:23:24,083
Oh, my God, there's somebody
still up there!

1173
01:23:25,334 --> 01:23:27,503
I'm going.

1174
01:23:28,588 --> 01:23:31,591
- I'll be here when you get back.
- Not coming back, chief.

1175
01:23:32,049 --> 01:23:33,176
Go! GO!

1176
01:23:39,265 --> 01:23:44,187
This scene that John Frazier and his
team of fire experts put together...

1177
01:23:44,395 --> 01:23:48,191
...I was really impressed by.
The amount of fire.

1178
01:23:48,441 --> 01:23:51,736
The fact that they pulled it off
so safely was incredible.

1179
01:23:52,445 --> 01:23:53,863
I'm gonna get you out of here!

1180
01:23:54,030 --> 01:23:56,908
Initially, we thought the suits
were flammable.

1181
01:23:57,116 --> 01:24:02,371
We did all of this experimenting
with fire retardant. Scary.

1182
01:24:02,580 --> 01:24:04,457
That's so scary, that...

1183
01:24:05,750 --> 01:24:09,212
The action in this sequence
is amazing, I think.

1184
01:24:09,378 --> 01:24:10,963
Like a moth to the flame.

1185
01:24:11,881 --> 01:24:14,342
What about my generous proposal?

1186
01:24:15,384 --> 01:24:18,221
Are you in or are you out?

1187
01:24:18,429 --> 01:24:20,973
It's you who's out, Gobby.
Out of your mind.

1188
01:24:21,474 --> 01:24:25,269
That's such a cheese line,
but really cute.

1189
01:24:25,603 --> 01:24:29,440
"It's you who's out, Gobby.
Out of your mind."

1190
01:24:30,066 --> 01:24:35,363
That's one of my favorite piece of
animation. The fluidity of movement.

1191
01:24:35,613 --> 01:24:38,824
They really captured the awkwardness
of the human form...

1192
01:24:38,991 --> 01:24:40,910
...and its grace at the same time.

1193
01:24:41,244 --> 01:24:43,871
I was always impressed by it.

1194
01:24:44,413 --> 01:24:47,959
I love the weapons, though.
This was another challenge.

1195
01:24:48,125 --> 01:24:51,504
We'd had this notion about
what Sam called "razorbats."

1196
01:24:51,671 --> 01:24:58,803
You know, the pumpkin bomb turns into
these flying boomerang-knife things.

1197
01:24:59,011 --> 01:25:01,347
Scary.

1198
01:25:02,098 --> 01:25:04,767
Great sound design in here as well.

1199
01:25:06,310 --> 01:25:09,272
Steve Flick did a great job in putting
these sounds together...

1200
01:25:09,438 --> 01:25:12,191
...with his team of effects cutters.

1201
01:25:15,027 --> 01:25:18,489
- M.J., will you stop goofing around?
- Harry, relax.

1202
01:25:20,992 --> 01:25:22,201
He's here.

1203
01:25:23,035 --> 01:25:25,454
- Are you ready?
- Yeah.

1204
01:25:26,372 --> 01:25:29,041
Aunt May. I'm sorry I'm late.

1205
01:25:29,208 --> 01:25:32,336
Work was murder.
I picked up a fruitcake.

1206
01:25:32,545 --> 01:25:35,965
Thank you, Mr. Osborn.
We're so glad you could come.

1207
01:25:36,215 --> 01:25:38,884
Who is this lovely young lady?

1208
01:25:39,051 --> 01:25:43,389
I'd like you to meet my father.
Dad, this is Mary Jane Watson.

1209
01:25:43,556 --> 01:25:46,225
I've been looking forward
to meeting you.

1210
01:25:46,475 --> 01:25:50,187
- Happy Thanksgiving, sir.
- Now, where is Peter?

1211
01:25:50,354 --> 01:25:52,732
He'd better have remembered
that cranberry sauce.

1212
01:25:58,487 --> 01:26:02,074
Oh, that's weird.
I didn't know he was here.

1213
01:26:05,077 --> 01:26:06,579
Peter?

1214
01:26:11,250 --> 01:26:12,835
Peter?

1215
01:26:14,754 --> 01:26:18,924
The Spider-Man mask wasn't made
to come off so easily.

1216
01:26:19,091 --> 01:26:22,178
James Acheson had to design one
just for that shot...

1217
01:26:22,345 --> 01:26:24,680
...that could be pulled off in an instant.

1218
01:26:24,930 --> 01:26:27,433
He knew it would never hold up
to scrutiny...

1219
01:26:27,600 --> 01:26:31,604
...so he made certain exactly what the
shot would be and designed it for that.

1220
01:26:32,438 --> 01:26:36,901
- Bit of a slob, isn't he?
- All brilliant men are.

1221
01:26:38,778 --> 01:26:41,614
- We actually put Tobey up there.
- You did?

1222
01:26:41,906 --> 01:26:43,741
You bet.

1223
01:26:50,206 --> 01:26:54,210
One of my favorite shots coming up
here. He looks up. He's not there.

1224
01:26:54,460 --> 01:27:00,549
We come back down, he's already
a step ahead of us, furious about it.

1225
01:27:09,517 --> 01:27:12,144
- Hey, everyone.
- Oh, Peter!

1226
01:27:12,311 --> 01:27:14,063
Sorry I'm late,
it's a jungle out there.

1227
01:27:14,230 --> 01:27:18,150
Had to beat an old lady with a stick
to get these cranberries.

1228
01:27:18,609 --> 01:27:21,445
Thank you.
Now then, everybody sit down...

1229
01:27:21,612 --> 01:27:23,155
...and we can say grace.

1230
01:27:24,740 --> 01:27:26,325
Parker.

1231
01:27:27,952 --> 01:27:31,288
I remember the turkey in this scene
had been sitting around for two days.

1232
01:27:31,497 --> 01:27:35,251
Put off this terrible,
rotting, horrible odor.

1233
01:27:35,459 --> 01:27:39,964
People had to pretend that it
was a delicious-looking thing.

1234
01:27:40,172 --> 01:27:42,133
In fact, it was nauseating.

1235
01:27:42,341 --> 01:27:46,554
Created an awful stench
that turned your stomach.

1236
01:27:55,563 --> 01:27:58,816
Why, Peter, you're bleeding.

1237
01:28:01,652 --> 01:28:06,991
I stepped off a curb and got clipped
by one of those bike messengers.

1238
01:28:07,158 --> 01:28:08,701
Well, let me see.

1239
01:28:08,868 --> 01:28:10,369
Oh, my goodness.

1240
01:28:10,661 --> 01:28:13,038
- That looks awful.
- No, it's nothing.

1241
01:28:13,205 --> 01:28:16,375
I'll get the first-aid kit.
Then we'll say grace.

1242
01:28:16,584 --> 01:28:21,881
This is the boys' first Thanksgiving
here, and we'll do things properly.

1243
01:28:22,840 --> 01:28:25,885
How did you say that happened?

1244
01:28:26,343 --> 01:28:28,053
Bike messenger.

1245
01:28:28,220 --> 01:28:30,222
Knocked me down.

1246
01:28:35,603 --> 01:28:39,231
- If you'll excuse me, I've got to go.
- Why?

1247
01:28:40,191 --> 01:28:43,569
Something has come to my attention.

1248
01:28:43,736 --> 01:28:47,406
- Are you all right?
- I'm fine, just fine.

1249
01:28:47,656 --> 01:28:50,201
This sequence is
such good moviemaking.

1250
01:28:50,409 --> 01:28:53,704
It's so entertaining,
such good, concise storytelling.

1251
01:28:53,913 --> 01:28:57,708
It's such a pivotal moment
in the movie...

1252
01:28:58,834 --> 01:29:04,006
...where everything comes together
and all the conflicts are...

1253
01:29:04,256 --> 01:29:08,010
All the rest of the movie
is set in motion.

1254
01:29:10,054 --> 01:29:12,806
Your mother was beautiful too.
They're all beautiful.

1255
01:29:12,973 --> 01:29:17,061
Until they're snarling after your trust
fund like a pack of ravening wolves.

1256
01:29:17,269 --> 01:29:18,521
You're wrong about her, Dad.

1257
01:29:19,063 --> 01:29:22,274
A word to the not-so-wise
about your little girlfriend:

1258
01:29:22,441 --> 01:29:26,278
Do what you need to with her,
then broom her fast.

1259
01:29:33,702 --> 01:29:38,457
In that moment with Mary Jane Watson,
I love where Kirsten is hurt...

1260
01:29:38,707 --> 01:29:42,378
...then she pulls it together
and you see some anger come out.

1261
01:29:42,586 --> 01:29:46,465
And then she decides she's not
gonna take it and she stands up.

1262
01:29:46,632 --> 01:29:49,051
Shut up about stuff
you don't understand!

1263
01:29:49,218 --> 01:29:54,682
I love watching her go through
those moments. That thought process.

1264
01:29:56,976 --> 01:30:00,312
<i>Spider-Man is all but invincible.</i>

1265
01:30:00,479 --> 01:30:03,649
<i>But Parker, we can destroy him.</i>

1266
01:30:03,816 --> 01:30:05,150
I can't.

1267
01:30:05,317 --> 01:30:08,320
<i>Betrayal must not be countenanced.</i>

1268
01:30:08,612 --> 01:30:10,823
<i>Parker must be educated.</i>

1269
01:30:12,992 --> 01:30:14,326
What do I do?

1270
01:30:14,493 --> 01:30:18,622
<i>Instruct him in the matters
of loss and pain.</i>

1271
01:30:18,789 --> 01:30:21,834
<i>Make him suffer.
Make him wish he were dead.</i>

1272
01:30:22,084 --> 01:30:23,335
Yes?

1273
01:30:23,502 --> 01:30:25,462
<i>And then grant his wish.</i>

1274
01:30:26,338 --> 01:30:27,673
But how?

1275
01:30:27,840 --> 01:30:32,177
<i>The cunning warrior attacks
neither body nor mind.</i>

1276
01:30:32,344 --> 01:30:33,512
Tell me how!

1277
01:30:33,721 --> 01:30:35,848
<i>The heart, Osborn.</i>

1278
01:30:36,140 --> 01:30:39,184
<i>First, we attack his heart.</i>

1279
01:30:41,020 --> 01:30:44,523
Give us this day our daily bread,
and forgive us our trespasses...

1280
01:30:44,773 --> 01:30:47,735
...as we forgive those
who trespass against us.

1281
01:30:47,985 --> 01:30:51,822
Lead us not into temptation,
but deliver us...

1282
01:30:53,866 --> 01:30:56,368
Rosemary was a real sport
to go through this...

1283
01:30:56,535 --> 01:31:00,664
...tremendous physical challenge,
being thrown about that room.

1284
01:31:00,873 --> 01:31:05,544
With the fans hitting her hard and all
the debris flying about around her.

1285
01:31:05,836 --> 01:31:08,547
I thought the CGI artist
did a great job...

1286
01:31:08,797 --> 01:31:11,884
...taking John Frazier's
explosion on set...

1287
01:31:12,134 --> 01:31:17,014
...composting it with her, then creating
CG debris elements that flew past her...

1288
01:31:17,264 --> 01:31:20,351
...that really put her
in an explosion sandwich...

1289
01:31:20,559 --> 01:31:23,062
...and sold the fact
that she was there.

1290
01:31:23,228 --> 01:31:24,396
You have to leave.

1291
01:31:24,563 --> 01:31:26,273
- What happened?
- Those eyes!

1292
01:31:26,482 --> 01:31:29,068
Those horrible yellow eyes!

1293
01:31:29,360 --> 01:31:34,406
The thing about the eyes, that scene
was the first day we had the suit...

1294
01:31:34,698 --> 01:31:37,660
...and we didn't have eyes
for the mask.

1295
01:31:37,910 --> 01:31:39,912
We'd never seen them.

1296
01:31:40,162 --> 01:31:43,874
We were shooting the scene, and we
were literally running back and forth...

1297
01:31:44,083 --> 01:31:48,837
...to the truck figuring out
how opaque should they be, how yellow.

1298
01:31:49,046 --> 01:31:52,091
And those eyes,
when we first did them...

1299
01:31:52,341 --> 01:31:56,762
...to get them to look right on camera,
you couldn't see through them.

1300
01:31:57,179 --> 01:31:59,682
This was originally three shots.

1301
01:31:59,890 --> 01:32:02,851
Don Burgess,
when we were shooting it...

1302
01:32:03,060 --> 01:32:06,313
...had the idea to put it all together
as one, which was a good idea.

1303
01:32:06,480 --> 01:32:12,194
It was Parker, the hands, the picture,
another angle of Parker, and his aunt.

1304
01:32:12,403 --> 01:32:16,949
Maybe it was five or six shots.
He put it all together with one move.

1305
01:32:17,199 --> 01:32:19,451
It turned out to be
the best thing for it...

1306
01:32:19,743 --> 01:32:25,124
...because it had a grace in it
that cutting would have broken up.

1307
01:32:27,126 --> 01:32:29,628
- Will she be okay?
- She'll be fine.

1308
01:32:29,795 --> 01:32:32,464
She's been sleeping all day.

1309
01:32:33,465 --> 01:32:36,218
- Thanks for coming.
- Of course.

1310
01:32:40,389 --> 01:32:43,308
How are you?
You okay about the other night?

1311
01:32:43,475 --> 01:32:47,146
Yeah, I'm fine. I just felt bad
about leaving Aunt May.

1312
01:32:47,396 --> 01:32:50,357
- Have you talked to Harry?
- He called me.

1313
01:32:50,816 --> 01:32:52,985
I haven't called him back.

1314
01:32:55,070 --> 01:32:56,780
The fact is...

1315
01:32:57,948 --> 01:33:00,743
- ...I'm in love with somebody else.
- You are?

1316
01:33:00,951 --> 01:33:04,747
Alvin Sargent did such a beautiful job
writing this speech by Peter.

1317
01:33:04,955 --> 01:33:09,585
It's so heartfelt
and it really gives you a glimpse...

1318
01:33:09,793 --> 01:33:13,797
...into the depths of his soul
and his feelings for her.

1319
01:33:14,506 --> 01:33:15,924
Trust me.

1320
01:33:16,175 --> 01:33:17,426
It's funny.

1321
01:33:19,428 --> 01:33:23,348
He's saved my life twice,
and I've never even seen his face.

1322
01:33:23,515 --> 01:33:26,935
- Oh. Him.
- You're laughing at me.

1323
01:33:27,144 --> 01:33:30,105
No, I understand.
He is extremely cool.

1324
01:33:30,314 --> 01:33:33,525
But do you think it's true, all the
terrible things they say about him?

1325
01:33:33,692 --> 01:33:37,696
No, no. Not Spider-Man,
not a chance in the world.

1326
01:33:37,905 --> 01:33:39,531
I know him a little bit.

1327
01:33:39,698 --> 01:33:42,618
I'm sort of his unofficial
photographer.

1328
01:33:42,826 --> 01:33:45,954
- Has he mentioned me?
- Yeah.

1329
01:33:46,288 --> 01:33:47,706
What'd he say?

1330
01:33:48,332 --> 01:33:49,666
I said...

1331
01:33:50,709 --> 01:33:55,047
He asked me what I thought about you.

1332
01:33:55,547 --> 01:33:58,175
One of my girlfriends
who saw this scene said:

1333
01:33:58,383 --> 01:34:05,140
"This is the speech every girl wants
a boy to make to her."

1334
01:34:05,390 --> 01:34:12,064
This is one of the many moments when
what we saw in that room in Berlin...

1335
01:34:12,356 --> 01:34:15,984
...is what happened in this scene
that made it worked so great.

1336
01:34:16,235 --> 01:34:19,988
- Yeah, Tobey was easy to work off of.
- Yeah.

1337
01:34:20,697 --> 01:34:25,327
Everything feels not quite normal.

1338
01:34:25,577 --> 01:34:31,500
Both Arthur Coburn and Bob Murawski
did a great job with this picture.

1339
01:34:31,750 --> 01:34:34,878
One of Bob's talents,
which you see in this scene...

1340
01:34:35,087 --> 01:34:39,258
...is his sense of performance
and take selections.

1341
01:34:39,550 --> 01:34:42,177
He really has a great talent
to be able...

1342
01:34:42,427 --> 01:34:45,889
...to be able to go in and watch all
the performances again and again...

1343
01:34:46,056 --> 01:34:50,269
...and choose what I think
is the best of the best.

1344
01:34:50,561 --> 01:34:54,606
That really plays in the moment...

1345
01:34:54,857 --> 01:34:57,776
...and cut them against each other.

1346
01:34:59,862 --> 01:35:01,989
It's as if you've...

1347
01:35:02,197 --> 01:35:05,075
...reached the unreachable.

1348
01:35:05,284 --> 01:35:09,246
His style of dress
is another thing entirely.

1349
01:35:13,292 --> 01:35:15,043
You said that?

1350
01:35:15,794 --> 01:35:18,130
Well, something like that.

1351
01:35:39,818 --> 01:35:42,446
That was Harry's first day on the set.

1352
01:35:42,613 --> 01:35:45,574
For some reason
he came in with black hair.

1353
01:35:45,824 --> 01:35:47,284
It was the weirdest thing.

1354
01:35:47,534 --> 01:35:52,539
We'd already figured out he was gonna
match his hair color to Willem Dafoe's.

1355
01:35:52,789 --> 01:35:56,126
He steps in to shoot,
and he's got black hair.

1356
01:36:02,174 --> 01:36:04,509
It gets a laugh in the theater,
this scene.

1357
01:36:04,676 --> 01:36:07,971
He's like, "Dad? Is that you?"
It's the most ridiculous...

1358
01:36:08,180 --> 01:36:12,976
But the laugh altogether
is such a signature of the character.

1359
01:36:14,603 --> 01:36:17,272
That's one of my funniest moments
in the picture.

1360
01:36:17,522 --> 01:36:21,860
He comes in and hears the rantings
and ravings of his father.

1361
01:36:22,110 --> 01:36:23,862
It's based on, for me...

1362
01:36:24,112 --> 01:36:28,617
I would come home and hear my mother
upstairs saying things...

1363
01:36:28,825 --> 01:36:34,623
...that she should have said to others,
but didn't have the guts. "Mom?"

1364
01:36:37,209 --> 01:36:39,795
He's loved her since the 4th grade.

1365
01:36:40,712 --> 01:36:46,009
He pretends like he doesn't, but
there's no one Peter cares for more.

1366
01:36:48,887 --> 01:36:50,681
I'm so sorry.

1367
01:36:53,141 --> 01:36:56,603
I haven't always been there for you,
Havel?

1368
01:36:58,230 --> 01:37:00,107
You're busy.

1369
01:37:00,357 --> 01:37:02,359
This was filmed in a great location
in L.A.

1370
01:37:02,609 --> 01:37:06,363
It was a huge mansion up
in the Hollywood Hills.

1371
01:37:06,613 --> 01:37:11,076
That's right. And Neil Spisak demanded
that we not shoot here.

1372
01:37:11,326 --> 01:37:15,622
He'd learned that they had shot
a scene from Batman here.

1373
01:37:15,831 --> 01:37:20,127
He demanded that I not photograph it
any way similar to Batman.

1374
01:37:20,377 --> 01:37:23,422
He made sure to decorate it
a very different way.

1375
01:37:23,672 --> 01:37:26,049
But I don't think anyone knows that.

1376
01:37:26,258 --> 01:37:30,846
At least they didn't until this moment,
when you happened to tell the viewers.

1377
01:37:31,054 --> 01:37:34,850
Bob came up with the idea
of putting that scare in at that moment.

1378
01:37:35,100 --> 01:37:38,645
- Actually, it may have been Paul's idea.
- Paul Hart, assistant editor.

1379
01:37:38,895 --> 01:37:41,690
Paul's idea to put a good scare,
jolt moment in there.

1380
01:37:41,940 --> 01:37:44,860
He did it as a joke.
Like many things...

1381
01:37:45,110 --> 01:37:49,781
...I realize some of the assistant's jokes
were better than my editor's great ideas.

1382
01:37:50,032 --> 01:37:52,784
So we took that...

1383
01:37:53,035 --> 01:37:56,955
...and Bob transformed it
into a full-fledged scare.

1384
01:37:59,041 --> 01:38:01,293
You were supposed to be asleep.

1385
01:38:02,169 --> 01:38:06,923
You know, you were about 6 years old
when M.J.'s family moved in next door.

1386
01:38:07,132 --> 01:38:11,136
And when she got out of the car,
and you saw her for the first time...

1387
01:38:11,720 --> 01:38:13,930
This was a great scene
that David Koepp wrote.

1388
01:38:14,097 --> 01:38:17,559
Reminds us of Peter's warmth
for Mary Jane ever since he was a child.

1389
01:38:17,809 --> 01:38:20,729
Helps set up the ending of the piece.

1390
01:38:20,979 --> 01:38:23,273
When he finally walks away from her.

1391
01:38:23,440 --> 01:38:26,443
You're reminded
just how much she means to him.

1392
01:38:26,693 --> 01:38:30,739
- She's still his girl.
- Well, isn't that up to her?

1393
01:38:30,947 --> 01:38:35,494
- She doesn't really know who I am.
- Because you won't let her.

1394
01:38:35,744 --> 01:38:38,830
You're so mysterious all the time.

1395
01:38:39,122 --> 01:38:41,833
Tell me, would it be so dangerous...

1396
01:38:42,084 --> 01:38:46,004
...to let Mary Jane know
how much you care?

1397
01:38:46,505 --> 01:38:48,924
Everybody else knows.

1398
01:38:51,843 --> 01:38:53,136
I'll be right back.

1399
01:38:53,845 --> 01:38:55,138
But...

1400
01:39:02,479 --> 01:39:04,481
Come on, pick up.

1401
01:39:04,648 --> 01:39:07,943
<i>- Hey, M.J.
- Hi. Sing your song at the beep.</i>

1402
01:39:08,985 --> 01:39:11,029
M.J., it's Peter. You there?

1403
01:39:11,321 --> 01:39:14,157
Hello? You there?

1404
01:39:14,658 --> 01:39:19,162
I'm just calling to check up on you.
Will you call me when you get in?

1405
01:39:19,329 --> 01:39:20,747
All right, well...

1406
01:39:21,164 --> 01:39:22,207
Don't...

1407
01:39:22,999 --> 01:39:25,210
Don't go up any dark alleys.

1408
01:39:25,377 --> 01:39:26,378
Hello?

1409
01:39:26,545 --> 01:39:28,463
That laugh.

1410
01:39:30,507 --> 01:39:32,843
Such a great cackle.

1411
01:39:33,051 --> 01:39:35,554
Where is she?

1412
01:39:40,392 --> 01:39:44,771
We actually played around with a lot
of different locations for this ending.

1413
01:39:45,021 --> 01:39:47,566
We knew we wanted to be up high.

1414
01:39:47,816 --> 01:39:53,822
That seemed like a requirement of the
storytelling. The Goblin who flies...

1415
01:39:54,072 --> 01:39:58,160
...and Spider-Man who swings,
and all that.

1416
01:39:58,410 --> 01:40:03,081
Then it hit us that
the 59th Street Bridge was the place.

1417
01:40:03,290 --> 01:40:07,502
Little did we know how difficult
it would be to execute.

1418
01:40:07,752 --> 01:40:10,213
Like the Times Square sequence...

1419
01:40:10,422 --> 01:40:15,177
...we couldn't actually go up there
and shoot on top of that bridge.

1420
01:40:16,595 --> 01:40:20,807
When we screened the movie
for the studio for the first time...

1421
01:40:21,016 --> 01:40:26,271
...they watched a sequence of M.J. on
the bridge, but there was no bridge.

1422
01:40:26,521 --> 01:40:28,607
And Spider-Man rescued her...

1423
01:40:28,773 --> 01:40:32,027
...but for half of the sequence,
there was no Spider-Man.

1424
01:40:32,235 --> 01:40:36,406
And we were trying to say:
"No, no, trust us. It's gonna be okay."

1425
01:40:48,919 --> 01:40:50,629
Goblin, what have you done?

1426
01:40:55,425 --> 01:41:00,055
I read about 400 kids
for those 10 kids in the tram.

1427
01:41:00,305 --> 01:41:04,601
I know you did. You were
in the casting room with them forever.

1428
01:41:04,809 --> 01:41:06,937
I spent about four days...

1429
01:41:07,145 --> 01:41:10,315
...with 9-year-olds screaming
at me and crying for me.

1430
01:41:10,482 --> 01:41:13,401
It was painful.
But they all did a great job...

1431
01:41:13,652 --> 01:41:18,782
...and it's really tough. They go
through a lot of emotions there.

1432
01:41:32,671 --> 01:41:34,256
Spider-Man!

1433
01:41:34,506 --> 01:41:39,010
For all the amount of hanging and
dropping I did, it doesn't look painful.

1434
01:41:39,261 --> 01:41:42,180
- It doesn't? It looks like that to me.
- Really? I did a lot?

1435
01:41:42,514 --> 01:41:46,309
But I was up there
for two weeks straight doing stuff.

1436
01:41:46,518 --> 01:41:49,312
Yeah, you were hanging and falling,
hanging and falling.

1437
01:41:49,521 --> 01:41:52,607
When you auditioned, Sam said:

1438
01:41:52,774 --> 01:41:55,318
"Are you in good shape?"
You made a muscle.

1439
01:41:55,527 --> 01:42:00,282
- You don't have a lot of muscle.
- I don't have any. I'm like, "Yeah, Sam.

1440
01:42:00,490 --> 01:42:03,201
Sure, whatever you want."

1441
01:42:04,411 --> 01:42:08,206
This bridge sequence is one of
the hardest scenes that I've ever done.

1442
01:42:08,415 --> 01:42:11,376
To think about how
the real bridge worked...

1443
01:42:11,626 --> 01:42:14,879
...and blocking the characters
on the real structure...

1444
01:42:15,046 --> 01:42:19,050
...verses the set pieces Neil
and his team built on stages...

1445
01:42:19,301 --> 01:42:22,220
...verses the CGI bridge
that had to be made...

1446
01:42:22,470 --> 01:42:24,139
...and the cheats that had to be made...

1447
01:42:24,306 --> 01:42:26,558
...relative to the real bridge
and the set pieces.

1448
01:42:26,975 --> 01:42:32,564
The under-bridge sets that went with
it. There was so much to keep in mind.

1449
01:42:32,814 --> 01:42:37,569
- It got very difficult, I remember.
- More so than Times Square sequence?

1450
01:42:37,819 --> 01:42:41,072
For me, it was, because I couldn't
walk the bridge.

1451
01:42:41,323 --> 01:42:46,202
These places didn't exist so that you
could scout and know personally.

1452
01:42:46,453 --> 01:42:50,915
A lot of it had to be kept in the mind
or just done through photographs.

1453
01:42:51,082 --> 01:42:55,045
So much dimensionality to it.
People moving from point A to point B.

1454
01:42:55,211 --> 01:42:57,881
I don't just mean left and right
or backwards and forward...

1455
01:42:58,048 --> 01:42:59,257
...but up and down.

1456
01:42:59,424 --> 01:43:01,760
Under, over, around the bridge.

1457
01:43:01,968 --> 01:43:05,055
You have to have a sense of it
in your mind to make the scene work.

1458
01:43:05,221 --> 01:43:07,390
So it was a real brain twister.

1459
01:43:07,557 --> 01:43:10,560
And always trying to keep in mind
where you are geographically...

1460
01:43:10,769 --> 01:43:13,730
...compared to Manhattan
and Roosevelt Island...

1461
01:43:13,897 --> 01:43:15,982
...to keep the continuity correct.

1462
01:43:16,191 --> 01:43:18,068
That's right.

1463
01:43:21,571 --> 01:43:23,823
Dan Sweetman,
a great storyboard artist...

1464
01:43:23,990 --> 01:43:29,287
...came in the second half of editing
and helped me re-work this sequence...

1465
01:43:29,496 --> 01:43:32,916
...based on original work that
Jeff Lynch, storyboard artist, had done.

1466
01:43:33,124 --> 01:43:36,002
Actually, before that,
based on work that I'd done...

1467
01:43:36,252 --> 01:43:39,798
...with another storyboard artist,
Mark Andrews.

1468
01:43:40,090 --> 01:43:43,301
Everybody really contributed
to this sequence.

1469
01:43:43,510 --> 01:43:47,013
Along with all the people
at Sony Pictures Imageworks.

1470
01:43:47,180 --> 01:43:51,226
Contributed incredible amount
under John Dykstra's supervision.

1471
01:43:56,648 --> 01:44:00,402
That's some more great animation
right there.

1472
01:44:05,740 --> 01:44:08,326
What's the groaning cow there?

1473
01:44:08,576 --> 01:44:11,621
That's the sound of strain on the...

1474
01:44:12,163 --> 01:44:15,458
Slowed down to 72 frames a second...

1475
01:44:15,667 --> 01:44:20,171
...the sound of thousands of pounds
of torque on this steel cable.

1476
01:44:22,424 --> 01:44:25,844
Tobey's brothers are in the tram too,
one of them was.

1477
01:44:26,136 --> 01:44:29,347
And John Dykstra,
visual effects supervisor...

1478
01:44:29,597 --> 01:44:32,183
...his daughter was one
of the tram kids.

1479
01:44:32,350 --> 01:44:38,773
John (Sally's stepson is one of the
tram kids. Everybody got in the act.

1480
01:44:39,816 --> 01:44:41,359
I got something for your ass!

1481
01:44:41,526 --> 01:44:43,319
You mess with Spidey,
you mess with New York!

1482
01:44:43,528 --> 01:44:46,448
You mess with one of us,
you mess with all of us.

1483
01:44:46,614 --> 01:44:48,867
Took a long time to reset
and do those shots.

1484
01:44:49,033 --> 01:44:53,455
All the prop guys and crew members
running around picking up rubber pipes.

1485
01:44:53,621 --> 01:44:55,373
A rubber chicken
was slipped in there.

1486
01:44:55,540 --> 01:44:58,501
But it took a long time
to reload all the New Yorkers...

1487
01:44:58,710 --> 01:45:02,338
- ...with objects to pelt Willem with.
- Yeah.

1488
01:45:02,547 --> 01:45:08,803
It's tough. You've got 150 extras that
you've treated badly for two days...

1489
01:45:09,012 --> 01:45:13,558
...then you give them objects to throw
at you. It's a dangerous job.

1490
01:45:18,354 --> 01:45:21,107
This was a set constructed
by Neil and his team...

1491
01:45:21,316 --> 01:45:24,611
...that we referred to
as the "hulking ruin."

1492
01:45:24,819 --> 01:45:28,615
A lot of beautiful
design work done in here.

1493
01:45:33,244 --> 01:45:37,499
Misery, misery, misery.
That's what you've chosen.

1494
01:45:38,333 --> 01:45:41,586
And this, to a large degree,
actually exists.

1495
01:45:41,836 --> 01:45:46,257
It's an old abandoned
smallpox hospital on Roosevelt Island.

1496
01:45:46,508 --> 01:45:48,676
But Neil did take his cue...

1497
01:45:48,927 --> 01:45:52,472
...from the actual hospital
that's there. It's interesting.

1498
01:45:56,267 --> 01:45:59,854
I thought the mixers did
a beautiful job in here.

1499
01:46:06,736 --> 01:46:08,821
Tobey did a great job looping too.

1500
01:46:08,988 --> 01:46:11,282
He had to come up
with 16 different ways to grunt.

1501
01:46:11,449 --> 01:46:12,575
Yeah, he did.

1502
01:46:19,374 --> 01:46:21,793
Peter Menzies came up with the web...

1503
01:46:21,960 --> 01:46:25,380
...Peter uses to stop the Goblin
the last second.

1504
01:46:25,588 --> 01:46:30,760
He was my second unit director
of photography just for this sequence.

1505
01:46:34,180 --> 01:46:37,809
You've spun your last web, Spider-Man.

1506
01:46:37,976 --> 01:46:41,312
Had you not been so selfish,
your girlfriend's death...

1507
01:46:41,479 --> 01:46:43,147
...would have been quick
and painless.

1508
01:46:43,314 --> 01:46:46,776
But now that you've really
pissed me off...

1509
01:46:46,985 --> 01:46:51,906
...I'm gonna finish her
nice and slow.

1510
01:46:56,828 --> 01:46:59,789
Sam came in one day and said,
"I want him to have a trident."

1511
01:46:59,998 --> 01:47:02,625
I don't know where that came from.

1512
01:47:02,834 --> 01:47:05,837
- With electric prods on the end.
- Right.

1513
01:47:07,213 --> 01:47:10,842
Get him, Spidey.
Your will is stronger than his.

1514
01:47:11,843 --> 01:47:13,761
Kick his buttocks.

1515
01:47:17,682 --> 01:47:23,855
Kim Kahana did great stunt here.
We let this wall fall down on him.

1516
01:47:27,692 --> 01:47:33,114
Willem did do almost all of his own
stunts, but that one was done by Kim.

1517
01:47:33,948 --> 01:47:39,662
Sam, I'm curious, is that arm coming out
of the rubble a wink to <i>Evil Dead?</i>

1518
01:47:39,871 --> 01:47:43,875
No, it's just a tribute to those old
Universal horror pictures.

1519
01:47:50,840 --> 01:47:53,384
The monster awakens.

1520
01:47:54,802 --> 01:47:57,555
The guys at A.D.I.,
Amalgamated Dynamics...

1521
01:47:57,764 --> 01:48:02,060
...did a great job with Willem's mask
right there, letting us beat it up.

1522
01:48:02,310 --> 01:48:05,021
- They really did.
- Yeah.

1523
01:48:09,567 --> 01:48:11,069
Mr. Osborn.

1524
01:48:11,277 --> 01:48:12,737
Thank God for you.

1525
01:48:12,904 --> 01:48:16,699
Great work on Spider-Man's costume
in various stages.

1526
01:48:16,908 --> 01:48:21,829
We had meetings about getting him
to the stage where you see him here.

1527
01:48:22,080 --> 01:48:27,210
And a lot of great work done
by Jim Acheson and Lisa Tomczeszyn...

1528
01:48:27,418 --> 01:48:31,589
...and his team of artists over there
in costume shop.

1529
01:48:31,798 --> 01:48:36,844
Jim had a mockup of the Spider-Man
outfit on a dummy he kept in a truck.

1530
01:48:37,095 --> 01:48:39,222
He'd follow me around,
location to location...

1531
01:48:39,430 --> 01:48:43,184
...lifting the truck's tailgate, saying:
"How about this, Sam?"

1532
01:48:43,434 --> 01:48:47,021
He'd take a razorblade to it and slice
away more pieces and more pieces.

1533
01:48:47,271 --> 01:48:50,108
He really worked long
and hard on that.

1534
01:48:50,400 --> 01:48:54,237
- The battle-ravaged Spider-Man look.
- Yeah.

1535
01:48:57,532 --> 01:49:00,910
It was difficult because
the whole costume works on tension...

1536
01:49:01,119 --> 01:49:04,247
...as Jim painstakingly told me
again and again.

1537
01:49:04,455 --> 01:49:09,460
You could only remove certain pieces
and still have it hold together properly.

1538
01:49:10,461 --> 01:49:14,966
Yeah, for the rain sequence,
you had to ruin one of our costumes...

1539
01:49:15,216 --> 01:49:20,471
...to make the head removable
and peeled up like that, and build...

1540
01:49:21,139 --> 01:49:22,974
...a special helmet.

1541
01:49:23,141 --> 01:49:27,979
This shot of Willem coming up
was actually shot later. This one.

1542
01:49:28,229 --> 01:49:31,482
He was already on another show.
He had to wear a wig.

1543
01:49:31,733 --> 01:49:35,611
He's more like the David Bowie
of Green Goblins.

1544
01:49:35,987 --> 01:49:37,864
Don't tell Harry.

1545
01:49:44,996 --> 01:49:48,458
The reason we re-did that shot
because we wanted him to say:

1546
01:49:48,666 --> 01:49:50,501
- "Don't tell Harry."
- Yeah.

1547
01:49:50,752 --> 01:49:55,590
Rather than it being an act of kindness
that Peter performs not tell Harry...

1548
01:49:55,840 --> 01:50:00,344
...we wanted him to fulfill
the last wish of Norman Osborn...

1549
01:50:00,511 --> 01:50:04,515
...this man who had been
the surrogate father to him.

1550
01:50:05,933 --> 01:50:10,271
So that he'd have an obligation,
a friendship...

1551
01:50:10,521 --> 01:50:15,359
...to perform these last acts,
to keep this dark secret.

1552
01:50:28,790 --> 01:50:31,834
Remember?
This was our first day in New York.

1553
01:50:32,043 --> 01:50:35,046
It was so cold and so windy.

1554
01:50:35,296 --> 01:50:40,384
Again, we had one day to shoot
this critical end scene in the movie.

1555
01:50:40,551 --> 01:50:43,805
But it was literally...
It must have been like 20 degrees.

1556
01:50:43,971 --> 01:50:45,932
I know what it's like
to lose a father.

1557
01:50:46,098 --> 01:50:50,019
The fellow playing the priest
kept asking me for a line.

1558
01:50:50,228 --> 01:50:54,148
I said, "I can't give it to you.
You're just a background player."

1559
01:50:54,357 --> 01:50:58,236
He had 10 different ideas of how
he could have a speaking part in this.

1560
01:50:58,402 --> 01:51:01,155
I swear on my father's grave,
Spider-Man will pay.

1561
01:51:01,322 --> 01:51:05,201
I really like James Franco's
performance in this scene.

1562
01:51:05,409 --> 01:51:07,745
I feel he's becoming his father.

1563
01:51:07,995 --> 01:51:12,333
Finally walking to that car that he was
so embarrassed of in the first scene.

1564
01:51:12,583 --> 01:51:17,088
He's very understated.
He's just brilliant in this last part.

1565
01:51:17,255 --> 01:51:23,094
You can feel the evil brewing
inside him, and the hatred.

1566
01:51:26,597 --> 01:51:31,269
That's a great shot.
He's almost walking to his destiny.

1567
01:51:36,107 --> 01:51:38,442
<i>No matter what I</i> do...

1568
01:51:38,609 --> 01:51:41,737
<i>...no matter how hard I try...</i>

1569
01:51:42,280 --> 01:51:46,117
<i>...the ones I love will always
be the ones who pay.</i>

1570
01:51:56,878 --> 01:51:59,213
You must miss him so much.

1571
01:52:00,131 --> 01:52:03,217
It's been so hard without him.

1572
01:52:06,137 --> 01:52:09,015
There's something
I've been wanting to tell you.

1573
01:52:10,808 --> 01:52:12,602
When I was up there...

1574
01:52:13,311 --> 01:52:16,147
...and I thought I was gonna die...

1575
01:52:17,773 --> 01:52:21,611
...there was only one person
who I was thinking of.

1576
01:52:22,904 --> 01:52:26,115
And it wasn't who I thought it'd be.

1577
01:52:27,241 --> 01:52:30,328
There's many questions
when you go to shoot a scene.

1578
01:52:30,536 --> 01:52:35,333
I remember Tobey and Kirsten,
they brought so much to this scene.

1579
01:52:35,583 --> 01:52:41,339
But one question was, they weren't
sure we should do the kiss at the end.

1580
01:52:43,007 --> 01:52:47,678
I really appreciate them going for it,
giving it a shot.

1581
01:52:47,970 --> 01:52:51,349
Because it turned out...
And you never know it at the time...

1582
01:52:51,557 --> 01:52:54,310
...but it wouldn't have even worked
without it.

1583
01:52:57,438 --> 01:53:01,859
We developed a great deal of trust
throughout the making of the movie.

1584
01:53:02,026 --> 01:53:05,947
They were willing to try things.
They learn to trust you...

1585
01:53:06,197 --> 01:53:09,200
...that if it doesn't work,
you won't keep it in the picture.

1586
01:53:09,367 --> 01:53:12,870
Laura was a big advocate of it too.
I thank her for that. Our producer.

1587
01:53:13,037 --> 01:53:14,664
I love you.

1588
01:53:15,498 --> 01:53:19,502
You had a great collaboration
with these two. They're gifted...

1589
